  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3281142682" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3281142682" />
    <a title="Vesna" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/59785585-vesna"><img alt="Vesna" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1639925815p2/59785585.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3281142682?book_show_action=true">Apr 24, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Vesna" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Vesna" href="/user/show/59785585-vesna">Vesna</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780199535583" href="/book/show/3213640-the-flowers-of-evil">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/59785585-vesna?shelf=translated">translated</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/59785585-vesna?shelf=classics">classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/59785585-vesna?shelf=poetry">poetry</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/59785585-vesna?shelf=read-in-2020-classics">read-in-2020-classics</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3281142682" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6168701311244710119">As Edna St.Vincent Millay wrote in the Preface to her collaborative translation with another poet (and her lover at the time) George Dillon, “The title <i>Les Fleurs du Mal</i> is not adequately translated as <i>Flowers of Evil</i>. These poems are flowers of doubt, flowers of torture, flowers of grief, flowers of blasphemy, flowers of weakness, flowers of disgust; …” This is not a comfortable journey, starting with his first poem addressed to the reader as “you — hypocrite Reader — my double — my brother!” (</span>
  <span id="freeText6168701311244710119" style="display:none">As Edna St.Vincent Millay wrote in the Preface to her collaborative translation with another poet (and her lover at the time) George Dillon, “The title <i>Les Fleurs du Mal</i> is not adequately translated as <i>Flowers of Evil</i>. These poems are flowers of doubt, flowers of torture, flowers of grief, flowers of blasphemy, flowers of weakness, flowers of disgust; …” This is not a comfortable journey, starting with his first poem addressed to the reader as “you — hypocrite Reader — my double — my brother!” (Lowell’s translation). Far from any flattery or courting of his reader, Baudelaire opens the gates into the dark inner world behind the conventional appearances of bourgeois life we all share. It’s the world of melancholies, miseries, sins, and even horrors, but also the inner world thriving for the purity of art and ideals of love. In my reading, I felt the question that Baudelaire keeps coming back to -and placing it to his reader to contemplate- is whether the ‘spleen’ of life can be overcome through art and love, or rather, whether poetry, music, and love can offer only a momentary escape and relief…<br><br>I read it in three different translations.<br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1366661737l/2441250.jpg" width="60" height="102" class="gr-hostedUserImg"> Chronologically first was <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/536387.The_Flowers_of_Evil" title="The Flowers of Evil by Charles Baudelaire" rel="nofollow noopener">St. Vincent Millay and Dillon’s edition</a> from the 1930s. Though I adore Millay’s poetry, I had many reservations about this translated collection. For one, the poems are rearranged which was jarring because, in all likelihood, Baudelaire had a specific structure and sequencing in mind, starting with the poems about the ideal of art and the ideal of love (devoted to three of his real-life muses, each with its own poem groupings), then followed by the melancholy and abyss of ‘spleen.’ The idea of tension between these two opposites, 'Idéal' and 'Spleen', in the first and longest section is completely lost in Millay &amp; Dillon’s rearrangement. They also didn’t respect the sequencing of the remaining 5 sections. Moreover, some well-known poems were inexplicably omitted. It was to their credit, however, that they included 5 out of 6 censored poems that the French authorities purged from the first edition for reasons of ‘obscenity’. The individual translations range from inspired to awkward and stilted. <br>Hardly 3 stars.<br><br>When the publisher sent their copy to the great <b>Paul Valéry</b> for comment, his reply was reprinted in the book as if it was an endorsement but his answer was much more ambivalent: “The quality of this translation is such that it would require the existence of another Baudelaire to convey an idea of it to the French reading-public.” I think the same can be said for any other translation of Baudelaire.<br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1388667125l/203220.jpg" width="60" height="102" class="gr-hostedUserImg"> <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/203220.Les_Fleurs_du_Mal" title="Les Fleurs du Mal by Charles Baudelaire" rel="nofollow noopener">Richard Howard’s collection</a> earned a prestigious prize for his translation and there is much fluidity and poise in his (mostly) free verse. All the same, a few poems were omitted (not sure why), there are no annotations, and probably the major deficiency is the absence of the face-to-face French original. <br>4 stars<br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1335618432l/3213640.jpg" width="60" height="102" class="gr-hostedUserImg"> Of all three collections, I found James McGowan for the <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/536387.The_Flowers_of_Evil" title="The Flowers of Evil by Charles Baudelaire" rel="nofollow noopener">Oxford World Classics</a> most enjoyable and informative. In comparison to Millay &amp; Dillon, it’s certainly more faithful to the original text. Also, unlike Howard, he at least attempts to recreate the musical element in Baudelaire’s poetry through rhythm and occasionally rhymes. <br>Overall then, it would be nearly 5 stars.<br><br>I’d like to mention Robert Lowell, another great poet, who translated only several poems and most of them can be found at fleursdumal.org.<br><br>A reader with even limited rudimentary knowledge of French is much more advantaged to read bilingual editions to enjoy the music of Baudelaire’s poems which is inseparable from their meanings, something that translations can never fully convey, as Paul Valéry implied. Mine is hardly a barebone conversational French, but it helped me to tremendously enjoy the melodic and dramatic aspects of Baudelaire’s poetic genius. Even better when heard along with a prose translation if needed. Here is the wonderful Jean-Louis Barrault, reciting the eternal <i>L'Invitation au voyage</i>:<br><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tvq4AM0h9vk">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tvq4A...</a><br><br>Some of the most enjoyable experiences for me were not in reading Baudelaire’s poetry, not even in the hands of a marvelous translator such as MacGowan, but in listening to Debussy’s, Fauré's, or Duparc’s songs with the text of some poems from <i>Les Flerus du Mal</i>.<br><br>The same <i>L'Invitation au voyage</i> with <b>Duparc</b>’s music and the great French baritone Gérard Souzay:<br><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-pUQEyoHyrA">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-pUQE...</a><br><br>Or <i>Harmonie du soir</i>, which I didn’t so much love in any translation, but listening to <b>Debussy</b>’s song (and Susan Graham’s gorgeous rendition) opened up the poetic and melodic beauty of the poem in its full splendor….<br><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZOMvqipswvM">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZOMvq...</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="6168701311244710119" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


